Niche table mein dekhiye ki har ek pheray (iteration) mein Beanshell ke andar backend mein kya ho raha tha:-
Loop Iteration	       Processing App	     linkk.getEntitlements() ne kya return kiya?	entitlements variable ki current state	       Result / Action
Pehla Phera (Loop 1)-----App A(AD------------[VPN_Group, HR_Group]-------------------------------[VPN_Group, HR_Group]-----------------Sahi chalega. AD ke dono groups remove karne ka plan ban jayega.
Dusra Phera (Loop 2)-----App B(Salesforce)-----null (Kyunki koi group nahi hai)------------------[VPN_Group, HR_Group]-----------------(Purana data bacha reh gaya)Yahan bug aaya! Salesforce ke liye bhi AD ke groups dobara chal gaye!

Aakhir yeh kyun hua?
Aapne loop ke andar bina curly brackets {} ke single-line if statement likha tha:
Java
if (linkk != null)
    entitlements = linkk.getEntitlements(); 
Java aur Beanshell mein agar aap curly brackets {} nahi lagate hain, 
toh compiler sirf uske turant baad wali ek line ko hi if ka hissa maanta hai. 
Uske niche aapne jo bhi likha, vo us conditional block se baahar chala jata hai.
Kyunki pure logic ka scope upar-niche block ho raha tha, 
toh jab code dusre application (Salesforce) par pahuncha aur use wahan null mila, 
toh Beanshell ke interpreter ne pichle application ki list ko memory se completely wipe/flush nahi kiya.
Natija ye hua ki niche wala if (entitlements != null) abhi bhi true ho gaya 
(kyunki memory wale dabbe mein abhi bhi AD ke groups pade hue the). 
Code ko laga ki ye Salesforce ke hi groups hain, 
aur usne Salesforce ke account request ke andar Active Directory ke groups ko remove karne ka galat request add kar diya! 
Isse aapka SailPoint plan fail ho jata.
